le for mere existence  with the certainty of losing it at last.', 1304, 0), (415284, 'Marriage is not just spiritual communion and passionate embraces  marriage is also three meals a day  sharing the workload and remembering to carry out the trash.', 62254, 0), (415285, 'We [Americans] cheerfully assume that in some mystic way love conquers all  that good outweighs evil in the just balances of the universe and that at the eleventh hour something gloriously triumphant will prevent the worst before it happens.', 41879, 0), (415286, 'There is no such thing as something for nothing.', 1187, 0), (415287, 'The mass of men lead lives of quiet desperation.', 1049, 0), (415288, 'Free man is by necessity insecure  thinking man is by necessity uncertain.', 190, 0), (415289, 'It is arrogance to expect that life will always be music.... Harmony  like a following breeze at sea  is the exception. In a world where most things wind up broken or lost  our lot is to tack and tune.', 62209, 0), (415290, 'Being unready and ill-equipped is what you have to expect in life. It is the universal predicament. It is your lot as a human being to lack what it takes. Circumstances are seldom right. You never have the capacities  the strength  the wisdom  the virtue you ought to have. You must always do with less than you need in a situation vastly different from what you would have chosen as appropriate for your special endowments.', 62223, 0), (415291, 'In nature there are neither rewards or punishments-there are consequences.', 1980, 0), (415292, 'Hope for a miracle. But don''t depend on one.', 62451, 0), (415293, 'Life guarantees a chance-not a fair shake.', 33, 0), (415294, 'Life is a perilous voyage.', 45901, 0), (415295, 'One must not hope to be more than one can be.', 63426, 0), (415296, 'The whole point of getting things done is knowing what to leave undone.', 65438, 0), (415297, 'We expect more of ourselves than we have any right to.', 24754, 0), (415298, 'Don''t fool yourself that you are going to have it all. You are not. Psychologically  having it all is not even a valid concept. The marvelous thing about human beings is that we are perpetually reaching for the stars. The more we have  the more we want. And for this reason  we never have it all.', 62254, 0), (415299, 'Try as hard as we may for perfection  the net result of our labors is an amazing variety of imperfectness. We are surprised at our own versatility in being able to fail in so many different ways.', 15506, 0), (415300, 'We set up harsh and unkind rules against ourselves. No one is born without faults. That man is best who has fewest.', 2542, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (415301, 'I can''t write a book commensurate with Shakespeare  but I can write a book by me.', 46913, 0), (415302, 'I have done what I could do in life  and if I could not do better  I did not deserve it. In vain I have tried to step beyond what bound me.', 2006, 0), (415303, 'Shall a man go and hang himself because he belongs to the race of pygmies  and not be the biggest pygmy that he can?', 1049, 0), (415304, 'The man with insight enough to admit his limitations comes nearest to perfection.', 62224, 0), (415305, 'The one important thing I have learned over the years is the difference between taking one''s work seriously and taking one''s self seriously. The first is imperative  and the second is disastrous.', 65439, 0), (415306, 'Growth begins when we start to accept our own weakness.', 3850, 0), (415307, 'To dream of the person you would like to be is to waste the person you are.', 33, 0), (415308, 'Of all the young men in America  only a few hundred can get into major league baseball  and of these only a handful in a decade can get into the Hall of Fame. So it goes in all human activity. ... Some become multimillionaires and chairmen of the board  and some of us must be content to play baseball at company picnics or manage a credit union without pay.', 5249, 0), (415309, 'At thirty a man should know himself like the palm of his hand  know the exact number of his defects and qualities. ... And  above all  accept these things.', 532, 0), (415310, 'No man can climb out beyond the limitations of his own character.', 42838, 0), (415311, 'You can''t make the Duchess of Windsor into Rebecca of Sunnybrook Farm. The facts of life are very stubborn things.', 55183, 0), (415312, 'Sometimes it is more important to discover what one cannot do  than what one can do.', 1317, 0), (415313, 'Learn to ... be what you are  and learn to resign with a good grace all that you are not.', 4754, 0), (415314, 'We cannot all be mas